<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-11-14T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-11-14T06:00:00-05:00" n="412" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d412">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/196: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-11-14T19:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">November 14,
                                        1921—7 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received November 14—4:35
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>396. An official in the Ministry of Communications and a representative
                            of Moss inform me that the recent default of the Chinese Government may
                            render it impossible to secure funds for the Federal wireless contract.
                            American prestige would be gravely injured should this contract fail to
                            be financed as it is a sound business project unconnected with the
                            solvency of the Chinese Government. The Department’s good offices to
                            ensure success are urgently requested.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>